[1] Re: ProMED-mail Hendra virus, equine - Australia (19): (QLD)
canine 20110728.2267
Date: Thu 28 Jul 2011
From: Caroline Reed <Caroline.Reed@healthscope.com.au> [edited]


You have had one sensible email about this dog, asking how valid is
the antibody test that has come up positive.

Serology testing in humans is notoriously unreliable, with low
specificity and sensitivity, and cross-reactions very real and
everyday occurrences.

Without knowing how long this test has been available, and how well
validated it has been with known positive and negative serum samples
(of which there can't be many positives), it is impossible to say what
this result means.

I have spent more than 30 years in human pathology, and the
interpretation of serology results is extremely difficult.

It would be very sad indeed to have this well and fit dog euthanised
on the basis of one possibly dodgy serology result.

The more critical results are the antigen results on the dog's saliva
(presumably by PCR or NAAT [nucleic acid amplification tests]?) which
are far more sensitive (and hopefully more specific) and a real
indication of infectivity.

--
Dr Caroline Reed MBBS FRCPath FRCPA
Pathologist - Medical Microbiologist
Healthscope Pathology
1868 Dandenong Road
Clayton
Australia
