[2] Re: ProMED-mail Hendra virus, equine - Australia (19): (QLD)
canine 20110728.2267
Date: Thu 28 Jul 2011
From: Jane Sykes <jesykes@ucdavis.edu> [edited]


The situation in regards to the dog with Hendra virus infection is
fascinating and highlights problems relating to the absolute
sensitivity, specificity, and positive predictive value of diagnostic
assays for zoonotic infectious disease. I appreciated the most recent
posting, including the message from David Thompson, that highlighted
issues relating to the humanity of euthanizing this dog or using the
dog for research purposes.

The popular media reports that describe the situation have too often
been misleading, because by saying the dog "tested positive for Hendra
virus" without further qualification of the nature and meaning of the
tests performed, they have implied that the dog was actively infected
with the virus and is therefore a real public health risk. It was
stated all too hastily in initial reports in the public media that the
recommendations were to euthanize the dog. Further consideration and
discussion is required in regards to the humanity of euthanizing an
apparently healthy dog that is someone's loved pet on the basis of a
single positive antibody test.

In my opinion, quarantine at this time and repeated investigation of
this dog's true antibody status and the possibility of virus shedding
seem like a more appropriate road to take.

--
Jane Sykes BVSc(Hons) PhD DACVIM
Professor of Small Animal Medicine, University of California, Davis
USA
President, International Society for Companion Animal Infectious
Diseases
<jesykes@ucdavis.edu>

[The question of test validation and sensitivity is a huge issue.
Furthermore, ProMED-mail reported yesterday (27 Jul 2011, archive no 20110727.2257) on information from 1994 indicating that dogs did not
shed virus and were not at risk of shedding virus.

How exceptionally sad that fear rules the day and the regulatory
authorities are so consumed by fear that they refuse to look at the
science already done. Then they think that taking millions of dollars
to solve a problem is great. Why not look at what has already been
done?

Why not learn from the animal? Study his behaviour, develop accurate
test, and determine if he can pass the virus to ferrets who are
apparently quite sensitive. Why put him in a different quarantine
site? The entire premises is already quarantined. So many questions,
and better alternatives than euthanasia.

We hope the regulatory authorities will listen to the previous
research and exercise some intelligent discretion, not just fear.
Until there is new information, we appreciate your comments but will
hold on posting until there is new information. - Mod.TG]

